ful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Kerdeston was born in 1325, in Claxton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Kerdeston 2nd Lord Kerdeston, was 23 and his mother, Alice Norwich, was 14. He married Ceclia Braose in 1354, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1391, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 66, and was buried in Reepham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1325–1391":"1325–1391","1328–Male":"1328–Surnud","1334–1401":"1334–1401","1350–1383":"1350–1383","1364–1421":"1364–1421","1303–1361":"1303–1361","1311–1342":"1311–1342","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1361":"1361","1391":"1391","14 August 1361":"14. august 1361","1325":"1325","1303":"1303","1401":"1401","1334":"1334","1311":"1311","1421":"1421","1354":"1354","1364":"1364","1342":"1342","about 1342":"umbes 1342","1328":"1328","Claxton, Norfolk, England":"Claxton, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kerdeston, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St Mary Church, Reepham, Broadland, Norfolk, England":"Reepham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kerdeston,Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kerdiston, Norfolk, England":"Kerdiston, Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1325–1391":"1325–1391","1328–Male":"1328–Kuollut","1334–1401":"1334–1401","